        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "08e788130e0ca7be",
        "text": "Location: The code will look in the directory wiki is started in, so where you run `wiki`. You can also specify the location by adding `--config <path to and name of config file>’\n\nOne thing to note is that the quotes used in the config file must be double quotes.\n\nSo, to start-up a wiki in your project’s directory you will want to create a config.json file there that looks like:\n\n{\n  “data”: “.\"\n}\n\nUsing the SivaSiva project as an example, you can change the default ‘home’ page of the site to SivaSiva by adding “home” to the config to specify the slug of the homepage.\n\n{\n  “data”: “.”,\n  “home”: “sivasiva”\n}\n\nWiki will create a `pages` and `status` in your project directory. As you are pushing the project directory up to github, you want to ensure that you are not putting anything in the config you don’t want to share.\n\nOne thing I have spotted, that will help with doing this for multiple projects, is that the config file can be split - this will become helpful when you have configuration items that you want to keep private. So, you put the common, and private, configuration into a file you load using `--config` while keeping any per project config in a config.json in the project directory. This becomes more useful as we more towards using OAuth, so you can keep the OAuth config out of the project and prevent inadvertently sharing private keys."
